\images",". Here are the main ones we'll be using:",[17,48,49],{},[50,51],"img",{"alt":52,"src":53},"blob.png - the monster","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Flearnexp\u002FLearningPixi\u002Fblob.png",[17,55,56],{},[50,57],{"alt":58,"src":59},"door.png - the door","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Flearnexp\u002FLearningPixi\u002Fdoor.png",[17,61,62],{},[50,63],{"alt":64,"src":65},"dungeon.png - the background","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Flearnexp\u002FLearningPixi\u002Fdungeon.png",[17,67,68],{},[50,69],{"alt":70,"src":71},"explorer.png - the player","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Flearnexp\u002FLearningPixi\u002Fexplorer.png",[17,73,74],{},[50,75],{"alt":76,"src":77},"treasure.png - the treasure","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Flearnexp\u002FLearningPixi\u002Ftreasure.png",[17,79,80],{},"And finally there's one big combined image:",[17,82,83],{},[50,84],{"alt":85,"src":86},"treasureHunter.png - Treasure Hunter","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002Flearnexp\u002FLearningPixi\u002FtreasureHunter.png",[17,88,89,90,95],{},"The original author also mentions that if you want to take a crack at other assets, you can grab them from the original author's ",[28,91,94],{"href":92,"rel":93},"https:\u002F\u002Fopengameart.org\u002Fusers\u002Fsharm",[32],"Lanea Zimmerman studio",".",[12,97,99],{"id":98},"the-other-file","The other file",[17,101,102,103,106,107,110,111,113,114,117],{},"While we're gathering assets, there's one thing worth noticing — under ",[43,104,105],{},"examples\u002Fimages"," you'll also find a ",[43,108,109],{},"treasureHunter.json",". The point of ",[43,112,109],{}," is to make it easy for us to map out where each individual image sits inside ",[43,115,116],{},"treasureHunter.png",". If the game we're building today were huge and complex, loading images one at a time would be a real pain. So usually you'd load the images using a JSON format instead, and if you need to tweak some details later, you just adjust this JSON.",[12,119,121],{"id":120},"wrapping-up","Wrapping up",[17,123,124,125,128,129,134],{},"OK, I'm guessing you already feel like this is getting complicated, so let's pause here and do a few basic exercises first. ",[28,126,33],{"href":30,"rel":127},[32]," also provides some simple ",[28,130,133],{"href":131,"rel":132},"https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002FZainking\u002FLearningPixi#%E4%BB%8E%E7%B2%BE%E7%81%B5%E5%9B%BE%E9%9B%AA%E7%A2%A7%E5%9B%BE%E4%B8%AD%E5%88%9B%E5%BB%BA%E7%B2%BE%E7%81%B5%E4%B8%BA%E4%BA%86%E9%98%B2%E6%AD%A2%E4%B8%8E%E7%B2%BE%E7%81%B5%E6%B7%B7%E6%B7%86%E6%88%91%E5%9C%A8%E4%B9%8B%E5%90%8E%E7%9A%84%E8%AF%91%E6%96%87%E4%B8%AD%E9%83%BD%E5%B0%86%E9%87%87%E7%94%A8%E9%9B%AA%E7%A2%A7%E5%9B%BE%E8%BF%99%E4%B8%80%E8%AF%91%E6%B3%95",[32],"practice",". We already know how to load single and multiple images, but we haven't tried loading through JSON yet. So next up, we'll practice how to take a single image and load it using JSON.",[12,136,138],{"id":137},"references","References",[140,141,142,148],"ul",{},[143,144,145],"li",{},[28,146,33],{"href":30,"rel":147},[32],[143,149,150],{},[28,151,94],{"href":92,"rel":152},[32],{"title":154,"searchDepth":155,"depth":155,"links":156},"",2,[157,158,159,160,161,162],{"id":14,"depth":155,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":155,"text":23},{"id":37,"depth":155,"text":38},{"id":98,"depth":155,"text":99},{"id":120,"depth":155,"text":121},{"id":137,"depth":155,"text":138},"JavaScript","2020-08-03 08:29:48","Time to put everything together. From here on we'll start combining the techniques from earlier in the series to build an actual little game called Treasure Hunter. This post covers where the game assets come from, which sprites we'll be using, and why loading images through a JSON file beats loading them one by one.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fpixijs-v5-26-treasure-hunter","2",{"ti